#X text 48 16 We can force the order of execution as this example shows. If we don't do this \, it's hard to guarantee we can read from the delay line without having a minimum delay of a block size. This is the same issue with [delwrite~] and [delread~] objects and other objects like [send~]/[receive~]. But the [del.in~] provides another structure as it has a dummy outlet to force the order of execution. This way you only need a subpatch to include [del.out~] object(s).;
#X connect 0 0 7 0;
#X connect 1 0 2 0;
#X connect 2 0 0 0;
#X connect 2 0 13 0;
#X connect 4 0 0 1;
#X connect 4 0 8 0;
#X connect 5 0 4 1;
#X connect 11 0 1 0;
#X connect 13 0 4 0;
#X restore 435 273 pd order;
